==English==
===Etymology===
See {{m|en|yada yada yada}}.
===Interjection===
{{en-interj}}
# Used three times in a row, or in combination with other words, to indicate part of a sentence which would be annoying to include, or which is incomprehensible, or which is just unimportant.
#* {{quote-book|en|year=2006|title=New York Murder Mystery: The True Story Behind the Crime{{...}}|passage=In fact, the academic said, crime trends are influenced far more by demographics and social forces and '''yadda, yadda, yadda''' than by police work.| author=Andrew Karmen}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|2002|June 2|Craig Medred|Trails committee goes a little wild|Anchorage Daily News|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=AS&p_text_direct-0=0F81CBE0357498C2&p_field_direct-0=document_id|page=G1
|passage=The planners held all the requisite public hearings, public discussions, public meetings, public forums, '''yadda''' public-this and '''yadda''' public-that.}}
